\prob{1}

We know that the centers are given by the $12$ fixed points of order
$8$ automorphisms of $X$ and the vertices given by the $32$ fixed
points of order $3$ automorphisms of $X$. Consider the automorphism
\[
(X,Y,Z) \mapsto (Y,iX,Z),
\]
which we easily check to have order $8$. The point $(1,Y,0)$ is fixed
by this automorphism if and only if $i/Y = Y \iff Y^2 = i \iff Y = \pm
\zeta_8$. We can replace $iX$ with $-iX$ to get fixed points $(1,\pm
\zeta_8^3,0)$. Then applying the two cyclic permutations of the
coordinates give us that the other $8$ fixed points (corresponding to
the automorphisms resulting from composing with the cyclic
permutations of the coordinates).

For order 3, consider the automorphism
\[
(X,Y,Z) \mapsto (Z,X,Y),
\]
which has two fixed points $(\zeta_3^2,\zeta_3,1)$ and
$(\zeta_3,\zeta_3^2,1)$. We can then multiply $X$ by $i^\alpha$ and
$Y$ by $i^\beta$ for $\alpha,\beta \in \{0,1,2,3,4\}$ (corresponding
to composing the above automorphisms with these same multiplication
automorphisms) to get the $32 = 2 \cdot 4^2$ fixed points.

