\prob{2}

\vspace{100pt}

Observe that any two (non-identified) edges intersect at precisely one
point, corresponding to the vertices of the polygon. Given the
orientation on the $4g$-gon pictured on the left, we deduce that
locally at this point the cycles are oriented as in the picture to the
right. It follows that the matrix $J^{(g)} \ce (C_i \cdot C_j)_{1 \le
  i,j \le 2g}$ is equal to
\[
\begin{pmatrix}
  0 & 1 & 1 & \cdots & 1 \\
  -1 & 0 & 1 & \cdots & 1 \\
  -1 & -1 & 0 & \cdots & 1 \\
  \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots \\
  -1 & -1 & -1 & \cdots & 0
\end{pmatrix}.
\]
Then since $C_{i+2g} = -C_i$ by definition of the identifications and
orientation, the full matrix $(C_i \cdot C_j)_{1 \le i,j \le 4g}$ is
just the block matrix
\[
\begin{pmatrix}
  J^{(g)} & -J^{(g)} \\ -J^{(g)} & J^{(g)}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]
Finally we show $\det(J^{(g)}) = 1$. The claim is obvious for $g=1$, and
we proceed inductively. Define the minors
\[
A_{i,j} \ce
\begin{pmatrix}
  J^{(g)}_{1,i} & J^{(g)}_{1,j} \\
  J^{(g)}_{2,i} & J^{(g)}_{2,j}
\end{pmatrix}
\]
and let $B_{i,j}$ be the complementary minor so that we have the
Laplace expansion
\[
\det(J^{(g)}) = \sum_{i < j} (-1)^{3+i+j} \det(A_{i,j})\det(B_{i,j}).
\]
Since $\det(A_{i,j}) = 0$ when $i,j \ge 3$ and $\det(A_{1,j}) =
\det(A_{2,j})$ and $\det(B_{1,j}) = \det(B_{2,j})$ when $j \ge 3$, it
follows that
\[
\det(J^{(g)}) = \det(A_{1,2})\det(B_{1,2}) = 1 \cdot \det J^{(g-1)} =
1.
\]

