\prob{3}

Let $D \in \Div(X)$ with $\deg(D) = g$. We have
\[
\textstyle{\phi(P_1,\ldots,P_g) = [D] \iff \sum P_i \sim D \iff \sum
  P_i \in |D|.}
\]
So to show $\phi$ is surjective, we must show $|D|$ is nonempty, i.e.,
that $\h^0(D) > 0$. But this is immediate from Riemann-Roch:
\[
\h^0(D) = 1 + g - \deg(D) + \h^0(K-D) = 1 + \h^0(K-D) \ge 1.
\]

Now suppose $D \ge 0$. We claim $\dim \phi^{-1}([D]) > 0 \iff \h^0(D)
> 1$. If $\h^0(D) = 0$ then $|D| = \{D\}$ so $\phi^{-1}([D])$ is just
a finite set, proving one direction. Conversely, assume $\h^0(D) >
1$. Suppose $x = (P_1,\ldots,P_g) \in \phi^{-1}([D])$ so $\sum P_i =
(f) + D \in |D| \simeq \P \O_D(X)$. Since the zeros and poles of $f
\in \O_D(X)$ vary continuously, at $f \in \P\O_D(X)$ we locally have
an embedding into a neighbourhood of $x \in \phi^{-1}([D])$. Since
$\dim \P\O_D(X) = \h^0(D) - 1 > 0$, we must have $\dim \phi^{-1}(D) >
0$.

Finally we note, by Riemann-Roch as above, $\h^0(D) > 1 \iff \h^0(K-D)
> 0$, or equivalently (by definition) $D$ is a special divisor.

