\prob{6}

\subprob{a}

Let $\{\omega_i\},\{\eta_i\}$ be two orthonormal bases of
$\Omega(X)$. For each $i$ write $\eta_i = \sum_i a_{ij} \omega_j$, and
note by orthonormality we must have $\sum_i a_{ij} \oline{a_{ik}} =
\delta_{jk}$ for any $j,k$. It follows that
\[
\sum_i \eta_i \otimes \oline{\eta_i} = \sum_{i,j,k} a_{ij}\omega_j
\otimes \oline{a_{ik}\omega_k} = \sum_{j,k} \omega_j \otimes
\oline{\omega_k} \sum_i a_{ij} \oline{a_{ik}} = \sum_j \omega_j
\otimes \oline{\omega_j},
\]
so indeed the Bergman metric $\rho$ is independent of the choice of
basis.

\subprob{b}

Choose a basis $\{\omega_i\}$ of $\Omega(X)$. Denote by
$\{\omega_i^*\}$  the dual basis of $\Omega(X)^*$. This determines an
isomorphism $\Jac(X) \simeq \Omega(X)^*/\H_1(X;\Z) \simeq
\C^g/\Lambda$ which gives $\Jac(X)$ the euclidean metric $\sum_i
d\omega_i^* \otimes \oline{d\omega_i^*}$ (via the local isomorphism
$\C^g \to \C^g/\Lambda$).

Now let $\phi \c X \to \Jac(X)$ be the Abel-Jacobi map, that is,
choose a basepoint $p \in X$ and define $\phi(q) \ce \int_p^q$. In
terms of the basis $\{\omega_i^*\}$ we then have $\phi(q) = \sum_i
(\int_p^q \omega_i)\omega_i^*$. It follows that
\[
\textstyle{\phi^*(d\omega_i^*) = d(\omega_i^* \circ \phi) = d(\int_p^q
  \omega_i) = \omega_i}
\]
and similarly $\phi^*(\oline{d\omega_i^*}) = \oline{\omega_i}$. So
finally, under the map $\phi$ the euclidean metric pulls back to the
Bergman metric $\sum_i \omega_i \otimes \oline{\omega_i}$. Since we
know $\phi$ is an injection from lecture, this implies that $\phi$ is
an isometry (given these metrics).
 
